{
  "firstValueMoment": "The first signed document arrives in the user's inbox, completing the signature loop they came to close.",
  "frictionScore": 78,
  "frictionRationale": "High band (67 to 100): value depends on a counterparty action. The user must verify email, verify phone, set a password, choose a plan, enter payment details, and send a document to a recipient before a signed agreement returns, which sits entirely outside the user's control.",
  "recurrenceSignal": "weak",
  "durableValue": "Retention: the flow delivers a one-time contract signature, and the case for return depends on whether the user has a second agreement to sign. Docusign is a per-project tool, not a daily habit, so recurrence tracks with contract cadence: a hiring manager or landlord returns monthly or quarterly, while a one-time buyer does not return at all. The flow makes no argument for why a user would send a second envelope after the first closes. The home screen offers Send your first document, not a reason to send a second, and the trial countdown (Trial ends in 14 days) is a billing reminder, not a retention hook. The signed document lands in the user's inbox as a completed artifact with no shared workspace, template library, or recipient relationship that pulls the user back in. A user who signs one contract has no reason the flow gives them to return until they have another contract to sign, and the flow does not create that need. This makes recurrence weak rather than absent: the tool supports repeat use, and some users will return because they have a second contract, but the flow offers no mechanism to increase that likelihood. Expansion: the trial gates premium features (templates, SMS delivery, AI speed-up) behind a $132/year Personal plan. A user who returns for a second signature and finds value in the gated features has a clear expansion path. However, expansion depends on retention, and retention here depends on the user having a second contract to sign, which the flow does nothing to generate. The payment gate is early (step 14) but deferred (no charge for 14 days), so it does not block activation, though it does create drop-off risk before the user sends the first envelope. Friction and recurrence together: a long path to first value is manageable when value recurs, but here the flow combines high activation friction with weak recurrence, because the user must clear 14 steps and wait on a counterparty to reach a value moment the flow gives them no reason to repeat. The work is not shortening the first-envelope path further but giving the user a reason to send a second envelope, which would turn weak recurrence into strong recurrence and make the activation investment pay off.",
  "topDropOff": "Payment details entry at step 14. A credit card is required to start the trial, 14 steps into the flow, before the user has sent a document or seen a signature. The $0 due today framing softens the gate, but requiring payment before value is delivered will lose users who are evaluating the tool or lack a card on hand.",
  "scopeNote": "This read covers the full path from marketing arrival to the moment a signed document returns, which depends on a recipient action not shown here. The friction and recurrence reads account for the counterparty dependency as the primary gate, and the 14 self-serve steps that precede it.",
  "experiments": [
    {
      "hypothesis": "Move the user into a shared envelope view with the recipient, where they see signature status update in real time, and surface a prompt to send a second envelope immediately after the first completes, with a prefilled recipient from the first envelope and a template suggestion based on the document type.",
      "rationale": "Weak recurrence is the constraint: users who reach value do not return because the flow offers no reason to send a second envelope. A shared status surface with a second-envelope prompt at the moment of completion captures the user when they are engaged and turns the first signature into a trigger for the second. Prefilling the recipient and suggesting a template removes friction from the return path and makes sending a second envelope feel like a natural next step rather than a cold start. This builds a return habit that the current flow does not create, which makes the 14-step activation investment durable rather than one-time.",
      "lever": "durable-value"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "After email verification (step 4), skip phone verification, password, plan selection, and payment, and drop the user directly into a send flow with a sample document and a single recipient field, so they send their first envelope in under 2 minutes, then collect payment only when the trial ends or the user sends a second envelope.",
      "rationale": "The current flow front-loads 10 gates before the user uploads a document, and requires payment before value is delivered. A verified email is enough identity to send a document, so cutting phone verification, password, plan choice, and payment moves the first envelope from step 18 to step 5, which gets significantly more users to the value moment. Collect payment later, when the user has seen value and is deciding whether to return. This reduces drop-off at the payment gate (step 14) and turns the first envelope into a qualification signal rather than a conversion gate.",
      "lever": "value-moment"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "On the home screen after trial start (step 17), replace the generic Send your first document card with a contract-type picker (NDA, offer letter, sales agreement, lease) that loads a prefilled template and a recipient field, so the user sends a real envelope instead of deciding what to send.",
      "rationale": "The current home screen assumes the user arrives with a document to upload, but many users arrive with a contract need and no prepared file. A contract-type picker with prefilled templates removes the upload step and the blank-page problem, so the user goes from intent to sent envelope in one click. This gets more users to the first signature by eliminating the need to leave Docusign, prepare a document, and return, which is where intent turns into abandonment.",
      "lever": "value-moment"
    }
  ]
}
